'use strict';


const Q=[
{id:1,cat:"React / Next.js",tech:["React"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is React and why do developers use it instead of plain HTML/JS?",a:"<strong>React</strong> is a JavaScript library made by Meta for building user interfaces. Instead of manually updating the DOM every time data changes, React lets you describe <em>what</em> the UI should look like for a given state, and it figures out the minimum DOM updates needed — through a process called reconciliation.<br><br>Developers use React because it enables: <strong>component-based architecture</strong> (reusable, self-contained pieces of UI), <strong>declarative rendering</strong> (describe the output, not the steps), a massive ecosystem, and a large community.",code:"// Plain JS — manually update the DOM\ndocument.getElementById('count').innerText = count;\n\n// React — declarative\nfunction Counter() {\n  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);\n  return (\n    &lt;div&gt;\n      &lt;p&gt;Count: {count}&lt;/p&gt;\n      &lt;button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}&gt;+&lt;/button&gt;\n    &lt;/div&gt;\n  );\n}",explain:'"React solves the pain of manually keeping the UI in sync with data. In plain JS, as your app grows, managing all the DOM updates becomes a nightmare. React lets you say: when count is 5, the UI looks like this — and it handles all the actual DOM work."',tip:"React is a library, not a framework. It handles only the UI layer. You combine it with React Router (navigation), Redux/Zustand (state), and Next.js (server-side rendering) to build a full application."},
{id:2,cat:"React / Next.js",tech:["React"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is a React component and what is the difference between functional and class components?",a:"A <strong>component</strong> is a reusable, self-contained piece of UI — like a LEGO brick. Your entire React app is a tree of components nested inside each other.<br><br><strong>Functional components</strong> are plain JavaScript functions that accept props and return JSX. They're the modern standard since React 16.8 introduced Hooks.<br><br><strong>Class components</strong> were the older way — they extend React.Component and use lifecycle methods like componentDidMount. You'll rarely write new class components today, but you'll encounter them in older codebases.",code:"// Functional component — modern standard\nfunction Greeting({ name }) {\n  return &lt;h1&gt;Hello, {name}!&lt;/h1&gt;;\n}\n\n// Class component — older style\nclass Greeting extends React.Component {\n  render() {\n    return &lt;h1&gt;Hello, {this.props.name}!&lt;/h1&gt;;\n  }\n}\n\n// Usage: &lt;Greeting name='Alice' /&gt;",explain:'"A component is basically a function that takes some input (props) and returns some UI (JSX). I always write functional components — they\'re simpler, shorter, and hooks give them all the power class components had. If I see a class component in a codebase, I know it\'s older code."',tip:"If you ever see this.state, this.props, or componentDidMount in React code, you're looking at a class component. Modern React uses useState, useEffect, and other hooks instead."},
{id:3,cat:"React / Next.js",tech:["React"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is JSX and how does it work under the hood?",a:"<strong>JSX</strong> (JavaScript XML) is a syntax extension that lets you write HTML-like code inside JavaScript. It's not valid JavaScript — it gets <em>compiled</em> by Babel into regular JavaScript function calls before the browser sees it.<br><br>Under the hood, every JSX element becomes a <code>React.createElement(type, props, children)</code> call, which returns a plain JavaScript object describing what should appear on screen.",code:"// What you write — JSX\nconst el = &lt;h1 className='title'&gt;Hello World&lt;/h1&gt;;\n\n// What Babel compiles it to\nconst el = React.createElement(\n  'h1',\n  { className: 'title' },\n  'Hello World'\n);\n\n// JSX rules:\n// 1. Use className instead of class\n// 2. Self-close empty tags: &lt;img /&gt; &lt;input /&gt;\n// 3. Must have one root element (or use &lt;&gt;&lt;/&gt; Fragment)",explain:'"JSX is just syntactic sugar — a friendlier way to write React.createElement() calls. I explain it as: it looks like HTML but lives inside your JavaScript, and Babel turns it into real JS before the browser ever sees it. The className vs class difference trips up everyone at first."',tip:"You can't use reserved JavaScript keywords as attribute names in JSX. That's why it's className (not class) and htmlFor (not for). Once you internalize this, JSX feels completely natural."},
{id:4,cat:"React / Next.js",tech:["React"],diff:"Easy",q:"What are props in React and how are they different from state?",a:"<strong>Props</strong> are data passed from a <em>parent</em> component to a <em>child</em>. They're read-only — a child cannot modify its own props. Think of them as the arguments you pass to a function.<br><br><strong>State</strong> is data managed <em>inside</em> a component that can change over time. When state changes, React re-renders the component with the new data. Think of state as the component's private memory.",code:"// Props — passed in, read-only\nfunction UserCard({ name, email }) {\n  return &lt;div&gt;{name} — {email}&lt;/div&gt;;\n}\n&lt;UserCard name='Alice' email='alice@x.com' /&gt;\n\n// State — managed inside, can change\nfunction Counter() {\n  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);\n  return (\n    &lt;button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}&gt;\n      Clicked {count} times\n    &lt;/button&gt;\n  );\n}",explain:'"I use an analogy: props are like the label on a package — they tell the component what it contains. State is like the content inside — it can change. A button receives its label as a prop (fixed), but tracks whether it\'s been clicked via state (changes). Key rule: props flow down, state lives inside."',tip:"A component re-renders whenever its state or props change. This is the core of how React keeps the UI in sync with data — you never manually update the DOM."},
{id:5,cat:"React / Next.js",tech:["React"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is useState and how do you use it?",a:"<code>useState</code> is a React Hook that lets you add a state variable to a functional component. It returns an array with two items: the current state value and a setter function to update it. When you call the setter, React re-renders the component with the new value.<br><br>The argument passed to useState is the <strong>initial value</strong> — used only on the first render.",code:"import { useState } from 'react';\n\nfunction LoginForm() {\n  const [email, setEmail]       = useState('');\n  const [isLoading, setLoading] = useState(false);\n  const [user, setUser]         = useState(null);\n\n  const handleSubmit = async () => {\n    setLoading(true);\n    const data = await login(email);\n    setUser(data);\n    setLoading(false);\n  };\n\n  return &lt;button onClick={handleSubmit}&gt;Login&lt;/button&gt;;\n}",explain:'"useState is the first hook every React developer learns. I explain it as: it\'s like a variable, but when it changes, React automatically redraws the screen. The key thing: never mutate state directly — always use the setter function, or React won\'t know it changed."',tip:"Never mutate state directly (e.g., state.push(item) or state.name = 'Alice'). Always use the setter: setState([...state, item]). Direct mutation won't trigger a re-render."},
{id:6,cat:"React / Next.js",tech:["React"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is useEffect and what is it used for?",a:"<code>useEffect</code> is a React Hook for performing <strong>side effects</strong> in functional components — anything that reaches outside the component: fetching data, subscriptions, updating the document title, or using browser APIs.<br><br>It takes two arguments: a function (the effect) and an optional <em>dependency array</em> that controls when it runs.",code:"function UserProfile({ userId }) {\n  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);\n\n  useEffect(() => {\n    fetch('/api/users/' + userId)\n      .then(r => r.json())\n      .then(data => setUser(data));\n  }, [userId]);\n  // []         = run once on mount only\n  // [userId]   = re-run when userId changes\n  // no array   = run after EVERY render (avoid!)\n\n  if (!user) return &lt;p&gt;Loading...&lt;/p&gt;;\n  return &lt;p&gt;{user.name}&lt;/p&gt;;\n}",explain:'"useEffect is the hook for \'do this after the component renders.\' The dependency array is the most common source of bugs: an empty [] means run once; listing variables means re-run when those change; omitting the array means run after every single render — almost never what you want."',tip:"Always clean up effects that create subscriptions or timers. Return a cleanup function: return () => clearTimeout(timer). This runs when the component unmounts, preventing memory leaks."},
{id:7,cat:"React / Next.js",tech:["Next.js"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is Next.js and what does it add on top of React?",a:"<strong>Next.js</strong> is a React framework built by Vercel. While React is just a UI library, Next.js adds everything you need for a complete production web app:<br><br><strong>File-based routing</strong>: Create app/about/page.tsx and you automatically have a /about route — no router configuration needed.<br><strong>Server-Side Rendering (SSR)</strong>: Pages rendered on the server for better SEO.<br><strong>Static Site Generation (SSG)</strong>: Pages pre-built at build time.<br><strong>Built-in optimizations</strong>: Image optimization, font loading, code splitting.",code:"// File-based routing — just create the file!\n// app/page.tsx            -> /\n// app/about/page.tsx      -> /about\n// app/blog/[id]/page.tsx  -> /blog/123\n\nexport default function AboutPage() {\n  return &lt;h1&gt;About Us&lt;/h1&gt;;\n}\n// No router config needed at all!",explain:'"I describe Next.js as React with a production toolkit built in. Plain React gives you the UI engine; Next.js gives you routing, server rendering, image optimization, and a deployment pipeline. For any real project beyond a simple demo, Next.js is my starting point."',tip:"Next.js has two routers: the older Pages Router (pages/ folder) and the newer App Router (app/ folder). All new projects should use the App Router — it supports React Server Components and is the direction the framework is moving."},
{id:8,cat:"React / Next.js",tech:["React"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is the virtual DOM and why does React use it?",a:"The <strong>virtual DOM</strong> is a lightweight JavaScript representation of the actual browser DOM. When state or props change, React creates a new virtual DOM tree and <em>compares it</em> with the previous one (diffing). React then calculates the minimum real DOM operations needed — called <strong>reconciliation</strong>.<br><br>This is faster than directly manipulating the real DOM on every change, because DOM operations are expensive and React batches and optimizes them.",code:"// React maintains a virtual copy of the DOM\n// When you call setUsers([...users, 'Charlie']):\n\n// React diffs old vs new virtual DOM\n// Finds: one new &lt;li&gt;Charlie&lt;/li&gt; needs adding\n// Updates ONLY that one real DOM node\n// Does NOT re-render the whole list\n\n// Without React — you'd do this manually:\n// const li = document.createElement('li');\n// li.textContent = 'Charlie';\n// document.querySelector('ul').appendChild(li);",explain:'"The virtual DOM is React\'s performance secret. Without it, every state change would mean re-rendering the whole page. With it, React only touches exactly what changed. I compare it to a building inspector who finds only the cracks in a wall and repairs just those spots, rather than demolishing the whole wall."',tip:"The virtual DOM is one of React's performance tools, but it's not magic. If you write very frequent small updates, consider useMemo, useCallback, or React.memo to prevent unnecessary re-renders."},
{id:9,cat:"JavaScript",tech:["JavaScript"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is the difference between null and undefined in JavaScript?",a:"Both represent the absence of a value, but with different meanings:<br><br><strong>undefined</strong> means a variable has been declared but not yet assigned a value — JavaScript sets this automatically. You'll see it when accessing an undeclared variable, an unpassed function parameter, or a missing object property.<br><br><strong>null</strong> is an intentional assignment meaning 'no value' or 'empty'. A developer explicitly sets something to null to say: this is intentionally empty right now.",code:"// undefined — JS sets this automatically\nlet name;\nconsole.log(name);    // undefined\n\nfunction greet(msg) {\n  console.log(msg);   // undefined if not passed\n}\ngreet();\n\n// null — developer sets intentionally\nlet user = null;      // explicitly 'no user yet'\nuser = fetchUser();   // now has a value\n\n// Checking for both:\nif (user == null)  { /* catches null AND undefined */ }\nif (user === null) { /* only catches null */ }",explain:'"The simplest way I explain it: undefined means I forgot to set this, null means I intentionally set this to nothing. In API responses, null usually means the field exists but has no value. undefined usually means the field wasn\'t included at all."',tip:"typeof undefined === 'undefined', but typeof null === 'object' — this is a famous JavaScript quirk kept for backwards compatibility. Never use typeof to check for null; use === null instead."},
{id:10,cat:"JavaScript",tech:["JavaScript"],diff:"Easy",q:"What are arrow functions and how are they different from regular functions?",a:"<strong>Arrow functions</strong> (=>) are a shorter ES6 syntax for writing functions. Beyond the conciseness, the key difference is the behaviour of <code>this</code>.<br><br>Regular functions have their own <code>this</code>, determined by <em>how the function is called</em>. Arrow functions don't have their own <code>this</code> at all — they inherit it from the <em>surrounding lexical scope</em>. This makes arrow functions safer and more predictable in callbacks and event handlers.",code:"// Regular function\nfunction add(a, b) { return a + b; }\n\n// Arrow — concise, implicit return\nconst add = (a, b) => a + b;\n\n// One parameter — no parens needed\nconst double = n => n * 2;\n\n// Multi-line — explicit return needed\nconst greet = name => {\n  return 'Hello, ' + name;\n};\n\n// 'this' difference — arrow inherits outer scope\nclass Timer {\n  start() {\n    setTimeout(() => {\n      this.tick(); // works! arrow uses Timer's 'this'\n    }, 1000);\n  }\n}",explain:'"Arrow functions are one of the ES6 features I use constantly. The short syntax is nice, but the real reason to prefer them in React is the this binding. With regular functions inside callbacks, this breaks. With arrow functions, this is always what you expect."',tip:"Arrow functions cannot be used as constructors (new arrowFn() throws an error), and they don't have their own arguments object. For methods that genuinely need their own this, use the function keyword."},
{id:11,cat:"JavaScript",tech:["JavaScript"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is the difference between forEach, map, and filter in JavaScript arrays?",a:"All three loop over an array, but they serve different purposes:<br><br><strong>forEach</strong> iterates for side effects and returns <code>undefined</code> — you can't chain it or produce a new array from it.<br><br><strong>map</strong> transforms each item and returns a <em>new array</em> of the same length — perfect for converting data shapes.<br><br><strong>filter</strong> returns a <em>new array</em> containing only items where the callback returns true.",code:"const nums = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];\n\n// forEach — side effects only\nnums.forEach(n => console.log(n));\n\n// map — transforms, same length\nconst doubled = nums.map(n => n * 2);\n// [2, 4, 6, 8, 10]\n\n// filter — only passing items\nconst evens = nums.filter(n => n % 2 === 0);\n// [2, 4]\n\n// Chaining map + filter\nconst result = nums\n  .filter(n => n > 2)\n  .map(n => n * 10);\n// [30, 40, 50]",explain:'"I explain it with a factory analogy: forEach is the worker who does a job on each item but gives nothing back. map is the machine that transforms every item into a new product. filter is the quality control gate that only lets certain items through. In React, map and filter are used constantly for rendering lists."',tip:"In React, you use .map() to render lists: users.map(user => <UserCard key={user.id} user={user} />). The key prop on each item is required so React can efficiently update the list."},
{id:12,cat:"JavaScript",tech:["JavaScript"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is destructuring in JavaScript and why is it useful?",a:"<strong>Destructuring</strong> is a shorthand syntax for extracting values from arrays or properties from objects and assigning them to variables in one clean line. It's one of the most-used ES6 features in modern JavaScript and React — you'll see it in function parameters, useState, and API responses constantly.",code:"const user = { name: 'Alice', age: 25, city: 'Mumbai' };\n\n// Without destructuring — verbose\nconst name = user.name;\nconst age  = user.age;\n\n// With destructuring — clean\nconst { name, age } = user;\n\n// Rename while destructuring\nconst { name: userName } = user; // userName = 'Alice'\n\n// Default values\nconst { city, country = 'India' } = user;\n\n// Array destructuring\nconst [first, second] = [10, 20, 30];\n\n// React useState uses array destructuring\nconst [count, setCount] = useState(0);",explain:'"Once you learn destructuring, you can\'t imagine coding without it. In React props, instead of writing props.name and props.age everywhere, I destructure at the function parameter: function Card({ name, age }) — cleaner and immediately shows what the component expects."',tip:"You can destructure nested objects: const { address: { city } } = user. And you can destructure directly in function parameters, which is very common in React component definitions."},
{id:13,cat:"JavaScript",tech:["JavaScript"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is the spread operator (...) and what are its common uses?",a:"The <strong>spread operator</strong> (<code>...</code>) expands an iterable (array, object, string) into individual elements. Its most common uses are: copying arrays/objects without mutation, merging arrays/objects, passing an array as individual function arguments, and immutably updating state in React.",code:"// Copy an array (new array, not a reference)\nconst copy = [...original];\n\n// Merge arrays\nconst merged = [...[1,2], ...[3,4]]; // [1,2,3,4]\n\n// Copy and update an object (immutable!)\nconst user = { name: 'Alice', age: 25 };\nconst updated = { ...user, age: 26 };\n// { name: 'Alice', age: 26 }\n\n// React state update — never mutate directly\nconst [items, setItems] = useState([]);\nsetItems([...items, newItem]); // spread + add\n\n// Function call with array as arguments\nconst nums = [1, 2, 3];\nconsole.log(Math.max(...nums)); // 3",explain:'"The spread operator is essential for immutable state updates in React. Instead of pushing to an array (which mutates), I spread the existing array and add the new item: setState([...state, newItem]). This gives React a new reference, so it knows to re-render."',tip:"The spread operator creates a shallow copy. If your array contains objects, the object references are copied — not the objects themselves. Modifying a nested object in a spread copy will still affect the original."},
{id:14,cat:"CSS / Tailwind",tech:["CSS"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is the difference between display: block, inline, and inline-block?",a:"The <code>display</code> property controls how an element occupies space on the page.<br><br><strong>block</strong>: Takes the full width of its container, starts on a new line. Width/height/margin/padding all work freely. Examples: div, p, h1.<br><br><strong>inline</strong>: Only takes up as much width as its content, flows with text, doesn't start on a new line. You CANNOT set width or height on inline elements. Examples: span, a, strong.<br><br><strong>inline-block</strong>: Flows inline like text, but you CAN set width and height like a block element.",code:"/* block — full width, new line */\ndiv { display: block; width: 50%; } /* works */\n\n/* inline — width/height ignored! */\nspan { display: inline; }\nspan { width: 200px; } /* NO effect */\n\n/* inline-block — best of both worlds */\n.badge {\n  display: inline-block;\n  width: 80px;   /* works! */\n  height: 24px;  /* works! */\n  /* AND flows inline with surrounding text */\n}",explain:'"I use a sentence analogy: block elements are like paragraphs — each gets its own line. Inline elements are like words — they flow with the text. Inline-block is like a small box sitting inside a sentence — it flows with text but you can give it a fixed size. Badges, buttons, and icons often use inline-block."',tip:"Flexbox and Grid have largely replaced the need for inline-block hacks. But understanding block vs inline is fundamental because many CSS properties (like width on a span) silently do nothing if the element is inline."},
{id:15,cat:"CSS / Tailwind",tech:["CSS"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is the difference between position: relative, absolute, fixed, and sticky?",a:"<strong>relative</strong>: Stays in normal flow, you can nudge it with top/left/right/bottom. Also creates a positioning context for absolutely positioned children.<br><br><strong>absolute</strong>: Removed from normal flow, positioned relative to its nearest positioned ancestor.<br><br><strong>fixed</strong>: Removed from flow, positioned relative to the viewport. Stays in place when the page scrolls. Use for navbars.<br><br><strong>sticky</strong>: Acts as relative until a scroll threshold, then behaves like fixed. Use for table headers.",code:"/* relative — stays in flow, small nudges */\n.nudge { position: relative; top: 10px; }\n\n/* absolute — positioned inside its parent */\n.parent  { position: relative; } /* establishes context */\n.tooltip { position: absolute; top: 100%; left: 0; }\n\n/* fixed — always visible on screen */\n.navbar { position: fixed; top: 0; left: 0; right: 0; }\n\n/* sticky — scrolls until threshold, then sticks */\nth { position: sticky; top: 0; }",explain:'"The most important thing: absolute positioning is always relative to the nearest ancestor with position: relative (or absolute/fixed/sticky). A tooltip that jumps to a random position usually means a parent element is missing position: relative."',tip:"For sticky to work, the element must have a top/bottom value set, and no ancestor in the scroll container can have overflow: hidden or overflow: auto — these silently break sticky positioning."},
{id:16,cat:"CSS / Tailwind",tech:["CSS","TailwindCSS"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is TailwindCSS and how is it different from writing regular CSS?",a:"<strong>TailwindCSS</strong> is a utility-first CSS framework. Instead of writing CSS files with custom class names, you apply pre-built utility classes directly in your HTML/JSX. Each class does one specific thing: <code>text-red-500</code> sets color, <code>p-4</code> sets padding, <code>flex</code> sets display to flex.<br><br>Traditional CSS requires switching between HTML and CSS files. Tailwind keeps everything in one place — the markup.",code:"/* Traditional CSS */\n.card {\n  padding: 16px;\n  background: white;\n  border-radius: 8px;\n  box-shadow: 0 2px 8px rgba(0,0,0,.1);\n}\n/* HTML: &lt;div class='card'&gt;...&lt;/div&gt; */\n\n\n/* Tailwind — utilities in HTML */\n/* &lt;div class='p-4 bg-white rounded-lg shadow-md'&gt; */\n/*   Content                                       */\n/* &lt;/div&gt;                                          */\n\n/* Responsive: */\n/* &lt;div class='text-sm md:text-base lg:text-lg'&gt; */",explain:'"Tailwind divides developers, but I love it for one key reason: I never have to context-switch between HTML and CSS files. Everything is visible in one place. The learning curve is just memorizing the class names, but after a week it becomes second nature. It also produces smaller CSS files by removing any unused classes at build time."',tip:"Tailwind classes are purged in production if unused. This means you can't build class names dynamically with string concatenation like 'text-' + color. Always write complete class names: use isActive ? 'text-red-500' : 'text-gray-500'."},
{id:17,cat:"CSS / Tailwind",tech:["CSS"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is Flexbox and what are its most useful properties?",a:"<strong>Flexbox</strong> is a CSS layout model for distributing space and aligning items in one dimension — either a row or a column. It makes centering elements, equal-height columns, and navigation bars dramatically simpler than older techniques (floats, tables, inline-block hacks).<br><br>You apply <code>display: flex</code> to a container, and all its direct children become flex items.",code:"/* Flex container controls layout */\n.navbar {\n  display: flex;\n  justify-content: space-between; /* main axis */\n  align-items: center;            /* cross axis */\n  gap: 16px;\n}\n\n/* Common values:\n   justify-content: flex-start | center | flex-end\n                    space-between | space-around\n   align-items:     flex-start | center | flex-end\n                    stretch (default)\n*/\n\n/* Center ANYTHING with 2 lines */\n.center {\n  display: flex;\n  justify-content: center;\n  align-items: center;\n}",explain:'"Flexbox solved the \"how do I center a div\" problem that plagued CSS for years. The two-line centering trick is one of the first things I teach. I also emphasize: flex properties go on the CONTAINER, not the items — beginners often put them in the wrong place."',tip:"flex-direction: column flips the axes — now justify-content controls vertical alignment and align-items controls horizontal. This is very useful for full-height layouts where you want to push a footer to the bottom."},
{id:18,cat:"Performance",tech:["JavaScript","React"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is a loading state and how do you handle it in React?",a:"When an async operation (like an API call) is in progress, the user needs visual feedback — this is the <strong>loading state</strong>. Without it, the page looks broken or frozen. The standard pattern in React is to maintain a boolean <code>isLoading</code> state that's true while data is being fetched and false once it arrives.",code:"function UserProfile({ id }) {\n  const [user, setUser]   = useState(null);\n  const [loading, setLd]  = useState(true);\n  const [error, setErr]   = useState(null);\n\n  useEffect(() => {\n    setLd(true);\n    fetch('/api/users/' + id)\n      .then(r => r.json())\n      .then(data => setUser(data))\n      .catch(err => setErr(err.message))\n      .finally(() => setLd(false)); // always runs\n  }, [id]);\n\n  if (loading) return &lt;Spinner /&gt;;\n  if (error)   return &lt;p&gt;Error: {error}&lt;/p&gt;;\n  return &lt;p&gt;{user.name}&lt;/p&gt;;\n}",explain:'"I always build components with three states: loading, error, and success. I handle them with early returns in that order — if loading is true, show a spinner and return early; if there\'s an error, show the error message and return early; otherwise render the data. This is the \'render three states\' pattern and it\'s the foundation of every data-fetching component I write."',tip:"The finally() block in a fetch chain runs whether the request succeeds or fails — making it the perfect place to setIsLoading(false). It ensures the spinner always stops, even on errors."},
{id:19,cat:"Performance",tech:["JavaScript"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is caching and why does it matter for web performance?",a:"<strong>Caching</strong> is storing a copy of data so that future requests for the same data can be served faster without repeating the expensive work. It's one of the most impactful performance techniques in web development.<br><br>Caching happens at multiple levels: the browser caches static files (JS, CSS, images); servers cache database query results; CDNs cache HTML responses close to the user geographically.",code:"// Simple in-memory cache in JavaScript\nconst cache = {};\n\nasync function getUser(id) {\n  if (cache[id]) {\n    return cache[id]; // served instantly!\n  }\n  const user = await db.findUser(id); // expensive!\n  cache[id] = user; // store for next time\n  return user;\n}\n\n// Next.js fetch caching (built in)\nconst data = await fetch('https://api.example.com/data', {\n  next: { revalidate: 60 } // cache for 60 seconds\n});\n\n// Browser cache via HTTP headers:\n// Cache-Control: max-age=31536000",explain:'"I explain caching with a library analogy: instead of ordering a new copy of a book every time someone asks for it, the library keeps a local copy on the shelf. The first request is slow (ordering the book); all subsequent requests are instant. The challenge is knowing when to restock — when the cached data has gone stale."',tip:"Cache invalidation — knowing when to update or delete a cached entry — is one of the hardest problems in computer science. A simple strategy: cache with a short expiry (e.g., 60 seconds) so stale data doesn't persist too long."},
{id:20,cat:"Node.js / Express",tech:["Node.js"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is Node.js and how is it different from running JavaScript in the browser?",a:"<strong>Node.js</strong> is a JavaScript runtime built on Chrome's V8 engine that lets you run JavaScript outside the browser — on your computer or a server. Before Node.js, JavaScript was browser-only.<br><br>Key differences: <strong>No DOM/window/document</strong> — those are browser-only APIs. Node.js has different built-in modules: <code>fs</code> (file system), <code>http</code> (network), <code>path</code> (file paths), <code>os</code> (operating system). It can also access the file system and create servers.",code:"// Browser JS — access to DOM\ndocument.getElementById('btn').addEventListener('click', fn);\n\n// Node.js — access to file system & network\nconst fs   = require('fs');\nconst http = require('http');\n\n// Read a file\nfs.readFile('data.txt', 'utf8', (err, data) => {\n  console.log(data);\n});\n\n// Create an HTTP server\nhttp.createServer((req, res) => {\n  res.write('Hello from Node.js!');\n  res.end();\n}).listen(3000);",explain:'"Node.js is what makes JavaScript a full-stack language. Before it, you\'d write your frontend in JS and your backend in Python or PHP. With Node.js, you can use the same language and share code between frontend and backend — a huge productivity win."',tip:"Node.js is single-threaded, but it handles thousands of concurrent connections through non-blocking I/O and the event loop. This makes it excellent for APIs and real-time apps, but not ideal for CPU-intensive tasks like image processing."},
{id:21,cat:"Node.js / Express",tech:["Node.js","Express.js"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is Express.js and how do you create a basic REST API with it?",a:"<strong>Express.js</strong> is a minimal web framework for Node.js that makes it much simpler to create web servers, define routes, handle requests, and send responses. It's the most popular Node.js framework and forms the backbone of thousands of production APIs.",code:"const express = require('express');\nconst app = express();\n\napp.use(express.json()); // parse JSON bodies\n\n// GET — fetch all users\napp.get('/api/users', (req, res) => {\n  res.json([{ id: 1, name: 'Alice' }]);\n});\n\n// GET — fetch one user\napp.get('/api/users/:id', (req, res) => {\n  const { id } = req.params;\n  res.json({ id, name: 'Alice' });\n});\n\n// POST — create a user\napp.post('/api/users', (req, res) => {\n  const { name, email } = req.body;\n  res.status(201).json({ id: 2, name, email });\n});\n\napp.listen(3000, () => console.log('Running'));",explain:'"Express makes creating an API feel like filling in a template. You call app.get, app.post etc., give each a URL pattern and handler function, and Express wires everything up. The req object gives you everything about the incoming request; the res object is how you send a response back."',tip:"REST API convention: GET fetches, POST creates, PUT/PATCH updates, DELETE removes. HTTP status codes matter: 200 OK, 201 Created, 400 Bad Request, 401 Unauthorized, 404 Not Found, 500 Internal Server Error."},
{id:22,cat:"Node.js / Express",tech:["Node.js"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is npm and what is package.json?",a:"<strong>npm</strong> (Node Package Manager) is the default package manager for Node.js. It lets you install, update, and manage third-party libraries. When you install a package, npm downloads it into a <code>node_modules</code> folder.<br><br><strong>package.json</strong> is a JSON file in the root of your project that describes it: its name, version, scripts (start, build, test), and — most importantly — the list of packages it depends on.",code:"// package.json\n{\n  \"name\": \"my-app\",\n  \"version\": \"1.0.0\",\n  \"scripts\": {\n    \"start\": \"node dist/index.js\",\n    \"dev\":   \"nodemon src/index.js\",\n    \"build\": \"tsc\"\n  },\n  \"dependencies\": {\n    \"express\": \"^4.18.2\"   // needed in production\n  },\n  \"devDependencies\": {\n    \"typescript\": \"^5.0.0\" // only during development\n  }\n}\n\n// npm install         — install all deps\n// npm install express — add a package\n// npm run dev         — run the 'dev' script",explain:'"package.json is the recipe card for your project. Anyone who clones your code can run npm install and get the exact same setup. I always add .gitignore to exclude node_modules — it can be hundreds of megabytes and is always regenerated from package.json, so there\'s no reason to commit it."',tip:"dependencies are packages your app needs in production. devDependencies are only needed during development (TypeScript, testing tools, linters). Installing with npm install -D adds a package to devDependencies."},
{id:23,cat:"Node.js / Express",tech:["Node.js"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is asynchronous code in Node.js and why does it matter?",a:"Node.js is <strong>single-threaded</strong> — it can only do one thing at a time. If it had to <em>wait</em> for each operation to complete (reading a file, querying a database, making an API call), it would be extremely slow — blocked on I/O most of the time.<br><br>Instead, Node.js uses <strong>asynchronous, non-blocking I/O</strong>: it starts an operation, moves on to handle other requests, and receives a callback/promise when the operation completes.",code:"// Synchronous (blocking) — bad for servers\nconst data = fs.readFileSync('big-file.txt'); // BLOCKS everything\n\n// Asynchronous (non-blocking) — good\nfs.readFile('big-file.txt', 'utf8', (err, data) => {\n  console.log(data); // called when done\n});\nconsole.log('This runs immediately, without waiting!');\n\n// async/await — modern, cleaner syntax\nasync function getUser(id) {\n  const user = await db.findById(id); // non-blocking\n  return user;\n}\n// While 'awaiting', Node handles other requests",explain:'"I use a coffee shop analogy: a blocking server is one cashier who takes your order, makes your coffee, then serves you — everyone waits. Node\'s async model is like a cashier who takes your order, hands it to the barista, takes the next customer\'s order, and delivers coffee when ready. The same person handles many customers simultaneously."',tip:"Even though Node is non-blocking for I/O, computationally expensive JavaScript (like complex math or image processing) DOES block the event loop. For CPU-heavy tasks, use worker threads or offload to a separate process."},
{id:24,cat:"Linux",tech:["Linux"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is Linux and why do developers need to know basic Linux commands?",a:"<strong>Linux</strong> is an open-source operating system kernel that powers the vast majority of web servers, cloud infrastructure (AWS, GCP, Azure), containers (Docker), and developer tools. As a web developer, even if you use Windows or macOS locally, your applications almost certainly run on a Linux server in production.<br><br>Knowing basic Linux commands means you can: SSH into a server, check running processes, read log files, move files, set permissions, and diagnose issues — all without a graphical interface.",code:"pwd              # Where am I right now?\nls -la           # List all files with details\ncd /var/www/html # Change directory\nmkdir my-app     # Make a new directory\nrm file.txt      # Remove a file (no recycle bin!)\nrm -rf folder/   # Remove folder recursively (be careful!)\n\ncat package.json # Print file contents\nhistory          # See previous commands\n\nCtrl+C           # Kill/stop the running process\nCtrl+L           # Clear the terminal screen",explain:'"Even if you never use Linux locally, you WILL need it the first time you SSH into a production server to debug an issue at 2am. Learning 20 basic commands takes a couple of hours and pays dividends for your entire career. The most important rule: be very careful with rm -rf — it permanently deletes with no undo."',tip:"Tab completion is your best friend in the terminal. Start typing a command or filename and press Tab — the terminal will autocomplete it. Double-tap Tab to see all possible completions."},
{id:25,cat:"Linux",tech:["Linux"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is a terminal, a shell, and what is Bash?",a:"A <strong>terminal</strong> is the application window you type commands into — it's just the UI (e.g., iTerm2, Windows Terminal).<br><br>A <strong>shell</strong> is the program running inside the terminal that interprets your commands — the actual command interpreter.<br><br><strong>Bash</strong> (Bourne Again Shell) is the most common shell on Linux. It's both a command interpreter and a scripting language — you can write .sh scripts to automate repetitive tasks.",code:"# Check which shell you're using\necho $SHELL      # /bin/bash or /bin/zsh\n\n# Basic Bash deploy script (save as deploy.sh)\n#!/bin/bash\necho 'Starting deploy...'\ngit pull origin main\nnpm install\nnpm run build\npm2 restart my-app\necho 'Deploy complete!'\n\n# Run it:\nchmod +x deploy.sh  # make executable\n./deploy.sh         # run it",explain:'"Knowing the difference between terminal and shell helps when Googling errors. Most Linux servers use Bash by default. Bash scripts are incredibly useful for automating repetitive tasks — like the deploy script above, which does in 2 seconds what would take 5 manual commands every time."',tip:"The shebang (#!/bin/bash) at the top of a script tells the OS which interpreter to use. Without it, the script might run with the wrong shell and behave unexpectedly. Always include it in shell scripts."},
{id:26,cat:"Linux",tech:["Linux"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is a process in Linux and how do you view and stop running processes?",a:"A <strong>process</strong> is a running instance of a program. Every time you run a command, a Node.js server, or Nginx, Linux creates a process with a unique <strong>PID</strong> (Process ID). Understanding processes is essential for checking if your server is running, finding what's consuming CPU or memory, or killing a stuck process.",code:"# View running processes\nps aux                     # all processes\nps aux | grep node         # filter for Node.js\ntop                        # live process viewer\nhtop                       # prettier live viewer\n\n# Find by name\npgrep node                 # prints PID of node processes\n\n# Kill a process\nkill 1234                  # graceful (SIGTERM)\nkill -9 1234               # force kill — use as last resort\npkill node                 # kill all node processes\n\n# Find what's on a port\nlsof -i :3000              # who is using port 3000?",explain:'"The most common scenario: I try to start my Node server and get \'Error: port 3000 already in use.\' I run lsof -i :3000 to find the PID of whatever is using that port, then kill that PID, and start my server again. Understanding this flow saves a lot of frustration."',tip:"kill -9 is a force kill — the process has no chance to clean up (close files, release database connections). Always try kill (SIGTERM) first and only use kill -9 if the process ignores it."},
{id:27,cat:"Linux",tech:["Linux"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is a log file and how do you read them in Linux?",a:"<strong>Log files</strong> are text files where applications record events, errors, requests, and other information over time. They're your primary debugging tool for production server issues. In Linux, system logs live in <code>/var/log/</code>.<br><br>The most important command is <code>tail -f</code> — it follows a log file in real time, showing new lines as they're written, invaluable for watching what your server is doing live.",code:"# Last 50 lines of a file\ntail -n 50 /var/log/nginx/error.log\n\n# Follow a log file in real time (Ctrl+C to stop)\ntail -f /var/log/nginx/access.log\n\n# Search for errors\ngrep 'ERROR' app.log\ngrep -i 'error' app.log   # case-insensitive\ngrep -n 'error' app.log   # show line numbers\n\n# PM2 app logs\npm2 logs              # real-time all apps\npm2 logs my-app       # specific app\npm2 logs --lines 100  # last 100 lines",explain:'"When something goes wrong in production, log files are your crime scene. I always start with tail -f to watch what\'s happening live, then grep for ERROR or the user\'s email to trace their specific requests."',tip:"Log rotation is important for long-running servers — log files grow indefinitely and can fill up disk space. Tools like logrotate automatically archive and compress old logs on a schedule."},
{id:28,cat:"MySQL",tech:["MySQL"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is a database and what is the difference between SQL and NoSQL?",a:"A <strong>database</strong> is an organized system for storing, retrieving, and managing data persistently — unlike variables in memory which disappear when a program stops.<br><br><strong>SQL databases</strong> (MySQL, PostgreSQL) store data in structured tables with rows and columns. They enforce a strict schema defined in advance.<br><br><strong>NoSQL databases</strong> (MongoDB, Redis) store data in flexible formats — documents, key-value pairs, graphs. No strict schema — each record can have different fields.",code:"-- SQL: structured tables, fixed columns\nCREATE TABLE users (\n  id    INT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT,\n  name  VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,\n  email VARCHAR(150) UNIQUE NOT NULL\n);\n\nINSERT INTO users (name, email)\nVALUES ('Alice', 'alice@example.com');\n\nSELECT * FROM users WHERE email = 'alice@example.com';\n\n// NoSQL (MongoDB): flexible documents\n// db.users.insertOne({ name:'Alice', email:'alice@x.com' })\n// db.users.insertOne({ name:'Bob', tags:['admin'] }) // OK!",explain:'"I use a filing cabinet analogy: SQL is a highly organized cabinet with labeled folders — everything has a specific place. NoSQL is more like sticky notes — fast to write, flexible in structure. For most standard applications with clear data relationships, I reach for SQL. For flexible, rapidly changing data structures, NoSQL."',tip:"The choice isn't either/or. Many modern applications use both: a SQL database (PostgreSQL/MySQL) for core business data, and a NoSQL database (Redis) as a cache layer for speed."},
{id:29,cat:"MySQL",tech:["MySQL"],diff:"Easy",q:"What are the basic SQL commands — SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, and DELETE?",a:"These four commands are the foundation of SQL — they're called <strong>CRUD</strong> (Create, Read, Update, Delete) operations and map to the four basic things you do with data in any application.",code:"-- SELECT (Read) — fetch data\nSELECT * FROM users;                    -- all rows\nSELECT name, email FROM users;          -- specific columns\nSELECT * FROM users WHERE age > 18;     -- with filter\nSELECT * FROM users ORDER BY name ASC;  -- sorted\nSELECT * FROM users LIMIT 10;           -- first 10 only\n\n-- INSERT (Create) — add new row\nINSERT INTO users (name, email)\nVALUES ('Alice', 'alice@example.com');\n\n-- UPDATE — ALWAYS use WHERE!\nUPDATE users\nSET email = 'new@example.com'\nWHERE id = 1;\n\n-- DELETE — ALWAYS use WHERE!\nDELETE FROM users\nWHERE id = 1;",explain:'"CRUD is the vocabulary of every application. Signup = INSERT. View profile = SELECT. Change password = UPDATE. Delete account = DELETE. Everything maps back to these four operations. I warn beginners: UPDATE and DELETE without a WHERE clause will affect every single row — always double-check your WHERE condition."',tip:"In production, never run UPDATE or DELETE without first running the equivalent SELECT with the same WHERE clause to verify you're targeting the right rows. A quick SELECT check has saved me from catastrophic mistakes many times."},
{id:30,cat:"MySQL",tech:["MySQL"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is a primary key and a foreign key in a database?",a:"A <strong>primary key</strong> is a column that uniquely identifies each row in a table. No two rows can have the same primary key, and it can never be NULL. It's the row's unique ID — typically an auto-incrementing integer or a UUID.<br><br>A <strong>foreign key</strong> is a column in one table that references the primary key of another table. It creates a relationship between tables and enforces <strong>referential integrity</strong> — you can't create a foreign key record that points to a non-existent primary key.",code:"-- Users table: id is the primary key\nCREATE TABLE users (\n  id    INT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT,\n  name  VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL\n);\n\n-- Posts table: user_id is a foreign key\nCREATE TABLE posts (\n  id      INT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT,\n  title   VARCHAR(200) NOT NULL,\n  user_id INT NOT NULL,\n  FOREIGN KEY (user_id) REFERENCES users(id)\n  -- Cannot insert a post with a non-existent user_id!\n);\n\n-- Query using the relationship\nSELECT posts.title, users.name\nFROM posts\nJOIN users ON posts.user_id = users.id;",explain:'"Primary and foreign keys are how relational databases model real-world relationships. Users have many Posts — that\'s a one-to-many relationship, modeled with a foreign key in the posts table. The database enforces this relationship: it prevents creating posts that point to non-existent users."',tip:"Using UUIDs as primary keys (instead of auto-incrementing integers) makes IDs safe to expose in URLs because they're not guessable. Sequential IDs like /users/42 let users guess that /users/43 exists."},
{id:31,cat:"MySQL",tech:["MySQL"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is the WHERE clause and how do you filter SQL queries?",a:"The <code>WHERE</code> clause filters which rows a SQL query affects. Without it, SELECT returns all rows, UPDATE modifies all rows, and DELETE removes all rows. You can combine conditions with <code>AND</code>, <code>OR</code>, and <code>NOT</code>, and use operators like <code>=</code>, <code>!=</code>, <code>LIKE</code> (pattern matching), <code>IN</code> (list of values), <code>BETWEEN</code>, and <code>IS NULL</code>.",code:"-- Basic WHERE\nSELECT * FROM users WHERE city = 'Mumbai';\n\n-- Multiple conditions\nSELECT * FROM users\nWHERE age >= 18 AND status = 'active';\n\n-- LIKE — pattern matching\nSELECT * FROM users WHERE email LIKE '%@gmail.com';\n-- % = wildcard (any characters)\n\n-- IN — match against a list\nSELECT * FROM users WHERE id IN (1, 5, 10, 15);\n\n-- BETWEEN — range\nSELECT * FROM orders\nWHERE created_at BETWEEN '2024-01-01' AND '2024-12-31';\n\n-- IS NULL — find missing values\nSELECT * FROM users WHERE phone IS NULL;",explain:'"The WHERE clause is the most important filter tool in SQL. I always emphasize: test your WHERE condition with a SELECT before running an UPDATE or DELETE — never trust your filter blindly on production data. LIKE with % is case-insensitive in MySQL by default, which is great for search features."',tip:"For full-text search, WHERE column LIKE '%keyword%' is slow because it can't use indexes — it scans every row. For production search features, use MySQL's FULLTEXT indexes or a dedicated search tool like Elasticsearch."},
{id:32,cat:"MongoDB",tech:["MongoDB"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is a document and a collection in MongoDB?",a:"A <strong>document</strong> is a single record in MongoDB — a JSON-like object (technically BSON) that stores key-value pairs. It's the MongoDB equivalent of a SQL row. Documents in the same collection can have different fields.<br><br>A <strong>collection</strong> is a group of related documents — equivalent to a SQL table. But unlike a SQL table, a collection has no fixed schema.",code:"// A MongoDB document\n{\n  _id: ObjectId('64a1b2c3...'), // auto-generated ID\n  name: 'Alice',\n  email: 'alice@example.com',\n  age: 25,\n  // Flexible! Different documents can have different fields:\n  address: { city: 'Mumbai', pin: '400001' },\n  tags: ['admin', 'beta-user']\n}\n\n// Basic operations\ndb.users.insertOne({ name: 'Alice', email: 'a@x.com' });\ndb.users.find({ name: 'Alice' });\ndb.users.findOne({ email: 'a@x.com' });\ndb.users.updateOne({ _id: id }, { $set: { age: 26 } });\ndb.users.deleteOne({ _id: id });",explain:'"A MongoDB collection is like a drawer labelled \'users\', and documents are the items inside it. Unlike a SQL table, each item in the drawer can have a different shape — one user might have an address field, another might not. This flexibility is both MongoDB\'s greatest strength (fast iteration) and its biggest risk (easy to end up with messy data)."',tip:"Every MongoDB document automatically gets an _id field (type ObjectId) if you don't provide one. It's a 12-byte unique identifier that encodes the creation timestamp — so you can extract the creation time from the _id even without a createdAt field."},
{id:33,cat:"MongoDB",tech:["MongoDB","Node.js"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is Mongoose and why do developers use it with MongoDB?",a:"<strong>Mongoose</strong> is an ODM (Object Document Mapper) for MongoDB in Node.js. It provides a layer of structure and validation on top of MongoDB's schema-less flexibility.<br><br>With raw MongoDB, you can insert any shape of data. Mongoose lets you define a <strong>Schema</strong> (the shape of a document) and a <strong>Model</strong> (a class for interacting with a collection). This gives you field validation, default values, custom methods, and TypeScript types.",code:"const mongoose = require('mongoose');\n\n// 1. Define a Schema\nconst userSchema = new mongoose.Schema({\n  name:      { type: String, required: true },\n  email:     { type: String, required: true, unique: true },\n  age:       { type: Number, min: 0, max: 120 },\n  createdAt: { type: Date, default: Date.now }\n});\n\n// 2. Create a Model\nconst User = mongoose.model('User', userSchema);\n\n// 3. Use the Model\nconst user = new User({ name: 'Alice', email: 'a@x.com' });\nawait user.save();\n\nconst found = await User.findOne({ email: 'a@x.com' });\nawait User.findById(id);\nawait User.updateOne({ _id: id }, { $set: { age: 26 } });",explain:'"Without Mongoose, nothing prevents you from inserting {foo: \'bar\'} into your users collection. With Mongoose, your Schema acts as a gatekeeper — it validates that required fields are present and correctly typed before anything reaches MongoDB. I always use Mongoose in Node.js + MongoDB projects for this safety net alone."',tip:"Mongoose connects to MongoDB using mongoose.connect(). Always store your MongoDB connection string in an environment variable, never hardcode it. Call connect() once when your app starts — not on every request."},
{id:34,cat:"MongoDB",tech:["MongoDB"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is ObjectId in MongoDB and how do you use it in queries?",a:"<strong>ObjectId</strong> is MongoDB's default type for the <code>_id</code> field — a 12-byte unique identifier that MongoDB auto-generates for every document. It looks like a 24-character hexadecimal string.<br><br>A key gotcha: ObjectId is not a plain string — it's a special type. When querying by _id, you must convert the string to an ObjectId, or the query will find nothing.",code:"// MongoDB shell\ndb.users.findOne({ _id: ObjectId('64a1b2c3d4e5f6a7b8c9d0e1') });\n\n// Mongoose — handles conversion automatically!\nconst user = await User.findById('64a1b2c3d4e5f6a7b8c9d0e1');\n// findById() is a Mongoose shortcut that auto-converts string -> ObjectId\n\n// Raw MongoDB Node.js driver — manual conversion needed\nconst { ObjectId } = require('mongodb');\nconst user = await db.collection('users').findOne({\n  _id: new ObjectId('64a1b2c3d4e5f6a7b8c9d0e1')\n});\n\n// Validate if a string is a valid ObjectId\nmongoose.Types.ObjectId.isValid(id); // true/false",explain:'"The ObjectId-vs-string confusion is one of the most common MongoDB bugs for beginners. In Mongoose, findById() handles the conversion for you. In raw MongoDB queries, you MUST wrap the string with new ObjectId(). The error you see when you forget this is: No document found — even when the document clearly exists."',tip:"You can validate whether a string is a valid ObjectId before using it: mongoose.Types.ObjectId.isValid(id). Use this in route handlers — if the ID in the URL isn't a valid ObjectId, return a 400 error immediately without hitting the database."},
{id:35,cat:"MongoDB",tech:["MongoDB"],diff:"Easy",q:"What are MongoDB operators like $set, $push, and $in?",a:"MongoDB update and query operations use <strong>operators</strong> — special keywords prefixed with $ that tell MongoDB exactly how to modify or match data. You don't overwrite entire documents with updates — you use operators to surgically modify specific fields.",code:"// $set — update specific fields (others unchanged)\nawait User.updateOne(\n  { _id: id },\n  { $set: { name: 'Bob', age: 30 } }\n);\n\n// $inc — increment a number\nawait Product.updateOne({ _id: id }, { $inc: { views: 1 } });\n\n// $push — add to an array\nawait Post.updateOne({ _id: id }, { $push: { tags: 'js' } });\n\n// $pull — remove from an array\nawait Post.updateOne({ _id: id }, { $pull: { tags: 'old' } });\n\n// $in — match any value in a list\nawait User.find({ role: { $in: ['admin', 'moderator'] } });\n\n// $gt / $lt / $gte / $lte — comparisons\nawait Product.find({ price: { $gt: 100, $lte: 500 } });",explain:'"Operators are the vocabulary of MongoDB. The most important one to understand first is $set — without it, you might accidentally replace the ENTIRE document with just the fields you\'re updating. Always use $set when you want to change specific fields and leave everything else untouched."',tip:"If you do updateOne({ _id: id }, { name: 'Bob' }) WITHOUT $set, MongoDB replaces the entire document with just { name: 'Bob' } — losing all other fields. Always use { $set: { name: 'Bob' } } to update specific fields safely."},
{id:36,cat:"Webpack",tech:["Webpack","JavaScript"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is a JavaScript module and why do we need module bundlers?",a:"A <strong>module</strong> is a self-contained file of JavaScript code that exports specific functions or values, and can import from other modules. Modules help you organize large codebases into logical, reusable pieces instead of one giant file.<br><br><strong>Module bundlers</strong> like Webpack combine all your modules into a few optimized bundle files, transform your code (TypeScript, JSX, SCSS), and optimize assets for the browser.",code:"// math.js — a module\nexport const add = (a, b) => a + b;\nexport const subtract = (a, b) => a - b;\n\n// user.js — imports from math.js\nimport { add } from './math.js';\nexport function calculateAge(birthYear) {\n  return add(new Date().getFullYear(), -birthYear);\n}\n\n// main.js\nimport { calculateAge } from './user.js';\nconsole.log(calculateAge(1998));\n\n// Webpack bundles all of the above into:\n// dist/main.bundle.js — one optimized file",explain:'"Think of Webpack as a packaging machine at a factory. You feed it lots of small, specialized parts (your modules), it assembles them into one efficient package (the bundle). It also runs the parts through different machines — one converts TypeScript, another compiles SCSS, another compresses images."',tip:"You don't always need to configure Webpack manually. Create React App, Vite, and Next.js all come with pre-configured bundlers. You only need to write webpack.config.js when you have custom requirements that the framework's defaults don't cover."},
{id:37,cat:"Webpack",tech:["Webpack","JavaScript"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is the difference between development and production build modes?",a:"Build tools treat <strong>development</strong> and <strong>production</strong> very differently because the priorities are opposite:<br><br>In <strong>development mode</strong>, the priority is developer experience — fast build times, readable code, source maps, and Hot Module Replacement.<br><br>In <strong>production mode</strong>, the priority is performance for end users — minification, tree shaking, code splitting, and asset optimization.",code:"// package.json scripts\n{\n  \"scripts\": {\n    \"dev\":   \"webpack serve --mode development\",\n    \"build\": \"webpack --mode production\"\n  }\n}\n\n// Development output:\n// main.bundle.js = 500KB (full, readable code)\n// Source maps: errors show your original file line numbers\n\n// Production output:\n// main.bundle.abc123.js = 120KB (minified)\n// Variable names shortened: function handleClick() -> function a()\n// Dead code removed\n// Assets compressed",explain:'"The golden rule: always run the production build before deploying, and always develop in dev mode. A common mistake is deploying a development build to production — the bundle is 4x larger and includes debugging tools users don\'t need."',tip:"Always run npm run build and check the output size before deploying. A production bundle that's mysteriously large (e.g., 2MB) usually means you accidentally imported an entire library when you only needed one function."},
{id:38,cat:"Webpack",tech:["Vite","JavaScript"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is Hot Module Replacement (HMR) and why is it useful during development?",a:"<strong>Hot Module Replacement (HMR)</strong> is a development feature that updates only the changed module in the browser <em>without refreshing the entire page</em>. When you save a file, instead of a full page reload (which loses all your state), HMR surgically replaces just the changed module and preserves everything else — including React component state.",code:"// Without HMR:\n// Save file -> full page reload -> lose all state\n// -> manually navigate back -> test\n// (takes 3-5 seconds every time)\n\n// With HMR (Vite or CRA):\n// Save file -> only that module updates\n// -> state is preserved -> test instantly\n// (takes ~50ms)\n\n// Vite enables HMR automatically — zero config!\nimport { defineConfig } from 'vite';\nimport react from '@vitejs/plugin-react';\n\nexport default defineConfig({\n  plugins: [react()]\n  // HMR is on by default!\n});",explain:'"HMR is one of those features that significantly changes how fast you can develop. Before it existed, every CSS tweak meant a full page reload and navigating back to the component you were working on. With HMR, tweaking styles feels instant. Vite\'s HMR is particularly fast because it only serves the changed file, not the whole bundle."',tip:"HMR sometimes loses state when you change the component's function signature or add/remove hooks. In those cases, it falls back to a full page reload. This is expected — React's rules of hooks require a fresh mount when hook order changes."},
{id:39,cat:"Webpack",tech:["Webpack","JavaScript"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is minification and why does it reduce JavaScript file size?",a:"<strong>Minification</strong> is the process of removing all unnecessary characters from source code without changing its functionality — spaces, newlines, comments, and long variable names are all stripped or shortened. The result is functionally identical code that's much smaller in bytes, which means faster downloads.",code:"// Original code — 190 bytes\nfunction calculateTax(price, taxRate) {\n  // Calculate final price including tax\n  const taxAmount = price * taxRate;\n  const finalPrice = price + taxAmount;\n  return finalPrice;\n}\n\n// Minified — 60 bytes (68% smaller!)\nfunction calculateTax(a,b){return a*(1+b)}\n\n// Webpack does this automatically in production.\n// Typical React app:\n// Dev bundle:  1,200 KB\n// Prod bundle:  220 KB (after minification + tree shaking)",explain:'"Minification is free performance — it happens automatically in a production build. You write clean, readable code and Webpack transforms it into the smallest possible version for the browser. The browser doesn\'t care that variable names are now single letters; it just executes the code. Users care about download speed, so minification is a direct UX improvement."',tip:"Related to minification is gzip/Brotli compression on the server. After minification, enabling gzip in Nginx compresses the file again during transfer — typically achieving another 60-80% size reduction. Both together make a huge difference."},
{id:40,cat:"Webhooks",tech:["Node.js","Express.js"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is an HTTP request and what are the common HTTP methods?",a:"An <strong>HTTP request</strong> is a message sent from a client (browser or React app) to a server, asking it to do something. Every API call, page load, and form submission is an HTTP request.<br><br>HTTP defines several <strong>methods</strong> that describe the intended action. Following REST conventions, each method has a specific purpose that developers universally agree on.",code:"// GET — retrieve data\nfetch('/api/users')              // get all users\nfetch('/api/users/42')           // get user #42\n\n// POST — create a new resource\nfetch('/api/users', {\n  method: 'POST',\n  headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },\n  body: JSON.stringify({ name: 'Alice' })\n});\n\n// PUT — replace a resource entirely\nfetch('/api/users/42', {\n  method: 'PUT', body: JSON.stringify(user)\n});\n\n// PATCH — update specific fields only\nfetch('/api/users/42', {\n  method: 'PATCH', body: JSON.stringify({ age: 26 })\n});\n\n// DELETE — remove a resource\nfetch('/api/users/42', { method: 'DELETE' });",explain:'"HTTP methods are the vocabulary of web communication. I use the CRUD acronym to connect them to database operations: POST = Create, GET = Read, PUT/PATCH = Update, DELETE = Delete. Following these conventions makes your API intuitive — any developer who sees GET /api/users/:id immediately knows what it does without reading documentation."',tip:"GET requests should never modify data — they should be safe and idempotent. Browsers cache GET requests aggressively, so accidentally using GET for data mutations can cause very confusing bugs."},
{id:41,cat:"Webhooks",tech:["Node.js"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is JSON and why is it used for sending data between frontend and backend?",a:"<strong>JSON</strong> (JavaScript Object Notation) is a lightweight, text-based data format for storing and exchanging structured data. It looks almost identical to a JavaScript object, but it's actually just a string — a universal language any programming language can read and write.<br><br>When your React app fetches data from an API, the server sends a JSON string. The browser parses it into a JavaScript object with <code>JSON.parse()</code>. When you send data, your app converts a JS object to a JSON string with <code>JSON.stringify()</code>.",code:"// JSON string (what travels over the network)\nconst jsonStr = '{\"name\":\"Alice\",\"age\":25,\"active\":true}';\n\n// Parse JSON string -> JavaScript object\nconst user = JSON.parse(jsonStr);\nconsole.log(user.name); // 'Alice'\n\n// Convert JavaScript object -> JSON string\nconst data = { name: 'Bob', tags: ['admin'] };\nconst toSend = JSON.stringify(data);\n\n// fetch() handles this for you:\nconst res = await fetch('/api/users');\nconst users = await res.json(); // calls JSON.parse\n\n// Sending JSON:\nfetch('/api/users', {\n  method: 'POST',\n  headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },\n  body: JSON.stringify({ name: 'Alice' })\n});",explain:'"JSON is the universal language of web APIs. I explain it as: your JavaScript object needs to cross a border (the network) to reach the server. JSON is the passport — it converts the object into a format every programming language understands. On the other side, the server uses JSON.parse() to convert it back into a native object."',tip:"JSON has strict rules: keys must be double-quoted strings (not single quotes), undefined values are stripped, and Date objects are serialized to strings. Always validate your JSON is well-formed — JSONLint.com is a quick online checker."},
{id:42,cat:"Webhooks",tech:["Node.js","Express.js"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is an API endpoint and how do you call one from a React app?",a:"An <strong>API endpoint</strong> is a specific URL on a server that accepts requests and returns data. Each endpoint typically represents a resource or action — like <code>GET /api/users</code> to retrieve users or <code>POST /api/auth/login</code> to log in.<br><br>From a React app, you call API endpoints using the browser's built-in <code>fetch()</code> function, typically inside a useEffect hook.",code:"function UserList() {\n  const [users, setUsers]   = useState([]);\n  const [loading, setLoad]  = useState(true);\n  const [error, setError]   = useState(null);\n\n  useEffect(() => {\n    fetch('https://api.example.com/users')\n      .then(res => {\n        if (!res.ok) throw new Error('Request failed');\n        return res.json();\n      })\n      .then(data => setUsers(data))\n      .catch(err => setError(err.message))\n      .finally(() => setLoad(false));\n  }, []); // empty array = run once on mount\n\n  if (loading) return &lt;p&gt;Loading...&lt;/p&gt;;\n  if (error)   return &lt;p&gt;Error: {error}&lt;/p&gt;;\n  return &lt;ul&gt;{users.map(u => &lt;li key={u.id}&gt;{u.name}&lt;/li&gt;)}&lt;/ul&gt;;\n}",explain:'"This useEffect + fetch pattern is the foundation of every data-fetching component in React. I always handle three states: loading, error, and success. I also check res.ok before calling res.json() — if the server returns a 404 or 500, fetch doesn\'t throw an error by default, which is a common gotcha."',tip:"For production apps, consider using React Query or SWR instead of raw fetch in useEffect. They handle caching, refetching, loading/error states, and pagination automatically — cutting a lot of boilerplate code."},
{id:43,cat:"Webhooks",tech:["Node.js","Express.js"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is an HTTP status code and what do the most common ones mean?",a:"<strong>HTTP status codes</strong> are 3-digit numbers sent in every HTTP response to indicate what happened. They're grouped by the first digit: 2xx = success, 3xx = redirect, 4xx = client error (your fault), 5xx = server error (server's fault).",code:"// 2xx — Success\n200 OK              // standard success for GET/PUT\n201 Created         // resource was created (POST)\n204 No Content      // success, nothing to return (DELETE)\n\n// 3xx — Redirects\n301 Moved Permanently // page has a new URL\n304 Not Modified      // cached version is still valid\n\n// 4xx — Client Errors (you sent something wrong)\n400 Bad Request     // malformed request or invalid data\n401 Unauthorized    // not logged in (no token)\n403 Forbidden       // logged in but no permission\n404 Not Found       // resource doesn't exist\n429 Too Many Requests // rate limited\n\n// 5xx — Server Errors\n500 Internal Server Error // unhandled exception in code\n503 Service Unavailable   // server is down/overloaded",explain:'"Status codes are the server\'s way of communicating what happened. The most important distinction: 401 means you\'re not logged in (redirect to login page), while 403 means you\'re logged in but don\'t have permission (show access denied). Confusing these two leads to broken auth flows."',tip:"In your Express APIs, always return meaningful status codes — not just 200 for everything. Clients use status codes to decide how to handle responses. A generic 200 on a failed validation makes it impossible to give users proper error messages."},
{id:44,cat:"Git & Tooling",tech:["Git"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is Git and why do developers use version control?",a:"<strong>Git</strong> is a distributed version control system — it tracks every change you make to your code files over time, lets you go back to any previous state, and enables multiple developers to work on the same codebase simultaneously without overwriting each other's work.<br><br>Without version control, you'd save files as app_v2_FINAL_v3.js and live in fear of deleting something important. Git gives you a complete history of every change, who made it, and why.",code:"# Basic Git workflow\ngit init                    # start tracking a project\ngit status                  # see what's changed\ngit add .                   # stage all changes\ngit add filename.js         # stage specific file\ngit commit -m 'Add login form validation'\n                            # save a snapshot with message\ngit log --oneline           # view compact history\n\n# Undo things\ngit checkout -- file.js     # discard changes to a file\ngit revert HEAD             # undo last commit (safe)\ngit reset --hard HEAD~1     # delete last commit (destructive!)",explain:'"Git is like a time machine for your code. Every commit is a snapshot you can return to. I explain it to beginners with: Have you ever deleted something and wished you could undo it? Git is the answer. The three-step workflow — add, commit, push — becomes muscle memory within a week."',tip:"Write meaningful commit messages that explain WHY you made the change. 'Fix bug' is useless history. 'Fix login redirect loop when token expires' is useful — it tells your future self exactly what problem was solved."},
{id:45,cat:"Git & Tooling",tech:["Git"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is a Git branch and why do developers use branches?",a:"A <strong>branch</strong> is an independent line of development — a separate workspace where you can make changes without affecting the main codebase. The default branch is usually called <code>main</code>.<br><br>Developers use branches to: work on a new feature without breaking the working version, fix bugs in isolation, experiment with ideas, and enable code review — you push a branch and teammates review your changes before they're merged into main.",code:"# Basic branching workflow\ngit branch                        # list all branches\ngit checkout -b feature/login-page # create + switch\n\n# ... make changes, commit them ...\ngit add .\ngit commit -m 'Add login page UI'\n\n# Push branch to GitHub\ngit push origin feature/login-page\n\n# Switch back to main\ngit checkout main\n\n# Merge your branch into main\ngit merge feature/login-page\n\n# Delete the branch after merging\ngit branch -d feature/login-page",explain:'"Branches are what make team collaboration possible. Without them, everyone would be pushing to the same branch and constantly breaking each other\'s work. The workflow I follow: create a branch for every feature or bug fix, commit to that branch, push it to GitHub, open a Pull Request for review, then merge. The main branch should always be deployable."',tip:"Name branches descriptively: feature/user-authentication, bugfix/login-redirect, hotfix/payment-crash. A branch name that describes the work makes PRs easier to understand and makes the git log readable at a glance."},
{id:46,cat:"Git & Tooling",tech:["Git"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is GitHub and how is it different from Git?",a:"<strong>Git</strong> is the version control tool that runs locally on your computer — it tracks your changes and manages history. <strong>GitHub</strong> is a cloud-hosted platform that stores Git repositories remotely, making it easy for teams to collaborate, review code, and backup their work.<br><br>GitHub also provides: Pull Requests (code review), Issues (bug/feature tracking), Actions (CI/CD automation), and Pages (free static site hosting). GitLab and Bitbucket are popular alternatives.",code:"# Connect your local repo to GitHub\ngit remote add origin https://github.com/user/my-app.git\n\n# Push your local code to GitHub\ngit push -u origin main\n\n# Clone someone else's repository\ngit clone https://github.com/user/their-app.git\n\n# Fetch and merge latest changes from GitHub\ngit pull origin main\n\n# Useful remote commands\ngit remote -v              # see remote URLs\ngit fetch origin           # download changes (no merge)\ngit pull                   # fetch + merge",explain:'"I explain it as: Git is the tool, GitHub is the platform. Git is like writing in a journal; GitHub is like storing that journal in a cloud backup that teammates can also read. Developers push their local commits to GitHub so code is backed up, teammates can see changes, and CI/CD systems can automatically test and deploy."',tip:"Never commit sensitive data (API keys, passwords, .env files) to GitHub, even in private repositories. If you accidentally commit a secret, consider it compromised — change it immediately. GitHub and bots scan repos for leaked secrets within minutes."},
{id:47,cat:"Git & Tooling",tech:["Git"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is a Pull Request (PR) and what is the code review process?",a:"A <strong>Pull Request (PR)</strong> is a GitHub feature that lets you propose merging one branch into another. Instead of merging directly, you open a PR to notify teammates: I've finished this work — please review it before it goes into main.<br><br>The process: developer opens a PR → teammates read the diff and leave comments → author makes requested changes → reviewers approve → PR is merged. This catches bugs, ensures consistency, spreads knowledge, and maintains code quality.",code:"# Typical PR workflow\n\n# 1. Create a feature branch and do your work\ngit checkout -b feature/password-reset\n# ... code and commit ...\ngit push origin feature/password-reset\n\n# 2. Go to GitHub -> click 'New Pull Request'\n#    Base: main (merge INTO)\n#    Compare: feature/password-reset\n#    Write a description of what and why\n\n# 3. Team reviews the code diff\n#    Comment on specific lines\n#    'Request changes' or 'Approve'\n\n# 4. Address feedback, push new commits to same branch\n#    The PR updates automatically\n\n# 5. Once approved -> 'Merge Pull Request'",explain:'"Pull Requests are the heartbeat of professional software development. They\'re not just about catching bugs — they\'re how knowledge spreads through a team. As a junior developer, PRs are your opportunity to learn from senior developers\' comments. I always write PR descriptions that explain WHY I made certain choices, not just what I did."',tip:"Keep PRs small and focused — ideally under 400 lines of changed code. Large PRs are hard to review thoroughly, so reviewers rubber-stamp them. If a feature is large, break it into multiple smaller PRs."},
{id:48,cat:"Git & Tooling",tech:["Git"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is .gitignore and what should you put in it?",a:"<strong>.gitignore</strong> is a text file in your project's root that tells Git which files and folders to <em>not track</em>. Files listed here won't appear in <code>git status</code>, won't be staged with <code>git add .</code>, and won't be committed or pushed to GitHub.<br><br>You should ignore: dependencies (node_modules), environment files (.env), build output (dist, build), OS-generated files (.DS_Store), and editor-specific files.",code:"# .gitignore\n\n# Dependencies — huge, always regenerated\nnode_modules/\n\n# Environment variables — NEVER commit secrets!\n.env\n.env.local\n.env.production\n\n# Build output — generated from source\ndist/\nbuild/\n.next/\n\n# OS files\n.DS_Store     # macOS\nThumbs.db     # Windows\n\n# Editor files\n.vscode/\n.idea/\n\n# Logs\n*.log",explain:'"The two most critical things to gitignore are node_modules (hundreds of megabytes, always regenerated by npm install) and .env files (they contain secrets that must never be public). I always create a .gitignore as the very first thing when starting a new project, before writing a single line of code."',tip:"If you accidentally committed a file that should be ignored, git rm --cached filename removes it from Git's tracking without deleting the actual file. Then add it to .gitignore and commit the removal."},
{id:49,cat:"Web Fundamentals",tech:["HTML","JavaScript"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is the DOM and how does JavaScript interact with it?",a:"The <strong>DOM</strong> (Document Object Model) is a programming interface the browser creates when it parses your HTML. It represents the document as a tree of objects where each HTML element is a node. JavaScript can read and modify this tree — adding, removing, or changing elements — to make pages interactive.<br><br>React, Vue, and Angular all ultimately work by manipulating the DOM. Understanding raw DOM manipulation helps you understand what frameworks do under the hood.",code:"// Selecting elements\nconst btn   = document.getElementById('myBtn');\nconst items = document.querySelectorAll('.item');\nconst first = document.querySelector('h1');\n\n// Changing content and styles\nfirst.textContent = 'New Heading';\nbtn.style.backgroundColor = 'blue';\nbtn.classList.add('active');\nbtn.classList.remove('hidden');\n\n// Responding to events\nbtn.addEventListener('click', () => {\n  console.log('Button clicked!');\n});\n\n// Creating and inserting new elements\nconst li = document.createElement('li');\nli.textContent = 'New item';\ndocument.querySelector('ul').appendChild(li);",explain:'"The DOM is the live, interactive version of your HTML. When you open DevTools and see the Elements panel, you\'re looking at the DOM. JavaScript can reach into that tree and change anything. React is essentially a very smart layer that manages DOM updates for you — understanding DOM manipulation helps you understand why React does what it does."',tip:"In React apps, avoid direct DOM manipulation with document.querySelector — React's virtual DOM can break if you manipulate the real DOM outside of React's knowledge. Use refs (useRef) if you genuinely need direct DOM access."},
{id:50,cat:"Web Fundamentals",tech:["HTML","CSS","JavaScript"],diff:"Easy",q:"What is responsive design and how do you implement it?",a:"<strong>Responsive design</strong> means building websites that look and work well on all screen sizes — from a 320px mobile phone to a 4K desktop monitor. Instead of building separate mobile and desktop versions, you write one codebase that adapts using CSS techniques.<br><br>The core tools are: <strong>media queries</strong> (apply CSS rules only at certain screen widths), <strong>flexible units</strong> (%, vw, rem instead of fixed px), <strong>Flexbox and Grid</strong> (naturally flexible layouts), and the <strong>viewport meta tag</strong>.",code:"&lt;!-- Required viewport meta tag in &lt;head&gt; --&gt;\n&lt;meta name='viewport' content='width=device-width, initial-scale=1'&gt;\n\n/* Mobile-first approach */\n.container {\n  display: grid;\n  grid-template-columns: 1fr; /* 1 column on mobile */\n}\n\n@media (min-width: 768px) { /* tablet and above */\n  .container { grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; }\n}\n\n@media (min-width: 1024px) { /* desktop */\n  .container { grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr); }\n}\n\n/* Tailwind responsive */\n/* &lt;div class='text-sm md:text-base lg:text-xl'&gt; */",explain:'"Responsive design starts with the viewport meta tag — without it, mobile browsers zoom out to render the desktop version and your media queries won\'t fire correctly. I design mobile-first: start with the mobile layout, then add media queries for larger screens. This is also Tailwind\'s approach — sm:, md:, lg: prefixes apply from that breakpoint upward."',tip:"Test responsive designs in Chrome DevTools (press F12, then click the device toolbar icon) to simulate different screen sizes. Always also test on a real phone — DevTools emulation is good but not perfect."}
];

